<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-453-210  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 453 210.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  May 1990 v111 n5 p89(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-end, high-technology facsimile for the 1990s.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Finlay, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The growth of the facsimile market has created two markets in one:the delivery of a product within minutes, and the delivery of anoriginal document.andP;  Overnight couriers still address the secondmarket, while fax machines are more popular for the first.andP;  Thebattle between the overnight couriers and fax manufacturescontinues in delivery of original documents.andP;  Fax prices have beenfalling sharply, and low-end units can now be purchased for $600to $800.andP;  Technology is developing to make documents look trulyoriginal to use in courts of law.andP;  However, this technology is notyet widespread and there is no big demand for it now.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FacsimileDocument deliveryTime ManagementCompetitionGrowthMarket Segmentation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>